\begin_layout Title
Problem Set 4 Microeconomics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Victor H.
 Aguiar 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
This version: October 2020
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(Expected Utility) Consider the following 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

portfolio choice
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem.
 The consumer (with preferences that admit an expected utility representation)
 has wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and a Bernoulli utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=ln(x)$
\end_inset

 there is a safe asset that has net real return of zero.
 There is also a risky asset with a random net return that has only two
 possible returns 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{1}$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-q$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be the amount invested in the risky asset so 
\begin_inset Formula $w-A$
\end_inset

 is the amount invested in the safe asset.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(i) Find 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 Does the consumer buys more or less of the risky asset as 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 increases?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
The consumer is solving the following maximization problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{A\in[o,w]}\{qu((1+R_{1})A+w-A)+(1-q)u((1+R_{0})A+w-A)\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Suppose the solution is interior, with 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=ln(x)$
\end_inset

, FOC is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q\frac{R_{1}}{R_{1}A+w}+(1-q)\frac{R_{0}}{R_{0}A+w}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Longrightarrow A=-w\frac{qR_{1}+(1-q)R_{0}}{R_{0}R_{1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Since the utility function is concave, so the consumer is risk averse.
 So, we can argue that 
\begin_inset Formula $qR_{1}+(1-q)R_{0}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Otherwise, the investor will never buy risky asset.
 WLOG, we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{1}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}<0$
\end_inset

.
 Otherwise, the consumer will either invest all her wealth in the risky
 asset (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}>0,\ R_{1}>0$
\end_inset

), or not invest in risky asset at all (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}<0,\ R_{1}<0$
\end_inset

).
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial A}{\partial w}=-\frac{qR_{1}+(1-q)R_{0}}{R_{0}R_{1}}>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(ii) A second (expected utility) consumer has a Bernoulli utility function
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=-exp(-x)$
\end_inset

.
 How does his consumption of the risky asset changes with wealth? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
We are solving the same maximization problem in part (i), with the new utility
 function, FOC is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
qR_{1}exp(-(1+R_{1})A-w+A)+(1-q)R_{0}exp(-(1+R_{0})A-w+A)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Longrightarrow qR_{1}exp(-R_{1}A-w)+(1-q)R_{0}exp(-R_{0}A-w)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Longrightarrow A=\frac{1}{R_{1}-R_{0}}ln\left[-\frac{R_{1}q}{R_{0}(1-q)}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
So 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial A}{\partial w}=0$
\end_inset

.
 That is investment in risky asset does not change with wealth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(iii) Compute the coefficient of absolute risk aversion 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=-\frac{u''(x)}{u'(x)}$
\end_inset

 for the first and second consumers.
 How these coefficients depend on wealth? How does this coefficient explains
 the answers in (i) and (ii).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
For 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=ln(x)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $u'(x)=\frac{1}{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u''(x)=-\frac{1}{x^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=\frac{1}{x}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 gets larger, 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)$
\end_inset

 gets smaller.
 Which means the wealthier the investor is, the less risk aver she is.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=-exp(-x)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $u'(x)=exp(-x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u''(x)=-exp(-x)$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the amount that investor allocates to risky asset is independent
 to her wealth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Non-expected utility theory.
 (Modeling) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
From class we had the Allais paradox behavior:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is finite in fact 
\begin_inset Formula $N=3$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Tabular
